sols_latex:
Let \emph{A} be the augmented matrix, that is,

\begin{align*}
A = \begin{bmatrix}
1 &-1 & 1 &2 \\ 
-2 & 1 & \alpha &-3 \\ 
1 & \alpha & -1 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

To begin the row-reduction, we add two multiples of the first line to
the second line and also subtract the first line from the third to
obtain

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & -1 & 1 & 2 \\ 
-2 & 1 & \alpha &-3 \\ 
1 & \alpha & -1 & 1
\end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix}
1 &-1 & 1 & 2 \\ 
0 & -1 & \alpha+2 & 1 \\ 
0 & \alpha+1 & -2 & -1
\end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix}
1 &-1 & 1 & 2 \\ 
0 & 1 & -(\alpha+2) & -1 \\ 
0 & \alpha+1 & -2 & -1
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

Then, subtract a factor of \emph{($\alpha$+2)} times the second row from the
last row and simplify

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 &-1 & 1 & 2 \\ 
0 & 1 & -(\alpha+2) & -1 \\ 
0 & \alpha+1 & -2 & -1
\end{bmatrix} &\sim \begin{bmatrix}
1 &-1 & 1 & 2 \\ 
0 & 1 & -(\alpha+2) & -1 \\ 
0 & 0 & (-(\alpha+2))(-(\alpha+1))-2 & -1+\alpha+1
\end{bmatrix} \\
&\sim \begin{bmatrix}
1 &-1 & 1 & 2 \\ 
0 & 1 & -(\alpha+2) & -1 \\ 
0 & 0 & \alpha(\alpha+3) & \alpha
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

We can now investigate what happens for different values of \emph{$\alpha$}.
Notice that the first line doesn't depend on \emph{$\alpha$} and so there is
nothing to conclude for the first line. For the second line, \emph{$\alpha$}
could make one of the terms vanish but there will still be a solution to
that equation if this happens. Therefore, the real power of \emph{$\alpha$}
comes from the third line. We can distinguish three cases for \emph{$\alpha$}:

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  When \emph{$\alpha$ = 0} the matrix will be \textbackslash{}begin\{bmatrix\}
\end{itemize}

1 \& -1 \& 1 \& 2 \textbackslash{}\textbackslash{} 0 \& 1 \& -2 \& -1
\textbackslash{}\textbackslash{} 0 \& 0 \& 0 \& 0
\textbackslash{}end\{bmatrix\}, and there will be \textbf{infinitely
many solutions}.

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  When \emph{$\alpha$ = -3} the matrix will be \textbackslash{}begin\{bmatrix\}
\end{itemize}

1 \& -1 \& 1 \& 2 \textbackslash{}\textbackslash{} 0 \& 1 \& 1 \& -1
\textbackslash{}\textbackslash{} 0 \& 0 \& 0 \& -3
\textbackslash{}end\{bmatrix\}, and there will \textbf{be no solution}.

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  When \emph{$\alpha$} is neither 0 nor -3, there will be a \textbf{unique
  solution}.
\end{itemize}
